0</published></entry><entry><id>30f7a4aec9918bb330de48d34434ef41</id><title>è€Œå®¶ä¿‚å’ªäººäººæ˜¯è‚¡ç¥ï¼Ÿ</title><updated>2025-08-09T11:53:32+08:00</updated><author><name>å³å„¼æ™‰</name></author><content type="html">&lt;p&gt;Published on: 2025-08-09T11:53:32+0800&lt;/p&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;div class="postmessage-content t_msgfont" id="postmessage_573534013"&gt;&lt;!-- google_ad_section_start --&gt;&lt;span id="postorig_573534013"&gt;ç™¼é”å–‡ä»Šæ¬¡&lt;img alt="" border="0" smilieid="49" src="https://www.discuss.com.hk/images/smilies/default2/smile_38.gif"/&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br/&gt;&lt;br/&gt;&lt;br/&gt; &lt;!-- google_ad_section_end --&gt;&lt;/div&gt;</content><link href="https://www.discuss.com.hk/viewthread.php?tid=32002807&amp;extra=page%3D1%26amp%3Bfilter%3D0%26amp%3Borderby%3Ddateline%26amp%3Bascdesc%3DDESC&amp;tr_h=1298815158689744ce4f0cf4_97207678"/><published>2025-08-09T11:53:32+08:00</published></entry><entry><id>df0390ff0c0752224527a0018ea3a0a9</id><title>é‡‘åƒ¹å°æ–¼å¤§æ‰‹æ²½ç©ºçŒ¶å¤ªäººé»è¬›......</title><updated>2025-08-09T12:03:25+08:00</updated><author><name>cowisstarting</name></author><content type="html">&lt;p&gt;Published on: 2025-08-09T12:03:25+0800&lt;/p&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;div class="postmessage-content t_msgfont" id="postmessage_573534093"&gt;&lt;!-- google_ad_section_start --&gt;&lt;span id="postorig_573534093"&gt;ä¿‚ä¸€å€‹å¢³å¢“&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br/&gt;&lt;br/&gt;&lt;br/&gt; &lt;!-- google_ad_section_end --&gt;&lt;/div&gt;</content><link href="https://www.discuss.com.hk/viewthread.php?tid=32002809&amp;extra=page%3D1%26amp%3Bfilter%3D0%26amp%3Borderby%3Ddateline%26amp%3Bascdesc%3DDESC&amp;tr_h=1298815158689744ce4f0cf4_97207678"/><published>2025-08-09T12:03:25+08:00</published></entry><entry><id>b09a977717f894e0deef52d3e27f8f94</id><title>19ä¸–ç´€è‹±åœ‹åš´ç¦åœ¨æœ¬åœŸéŠ·å”®é´‰ç‰‡ï¼Œå»æ•…æ„å¤§é‡å‡ºå£åˆ°ä¸­åœ‹ï¼Œæœ€çµ‚å¼•çˆ†é´‰ç‰‡æˆ°çˆ­ï¼</title><updated>2025-08-09T12:19:54+08:00</updated><author><name>äºè£”é–¹å‰²çŠ¬1842</name></author><content type="html">&lt;p&gt;Published on: 2025-08-09T12:19:54+0800&lt;/p&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;div class="postmessage-content t_msgfont" id="postmessage_573534258"&gt;&lt;!-- google_ad_section_start --&gt;&lt;span id="postorig_573534258"&gt;é–¹å‰²ä½¬æ­£ä¸€ä»†è¡—å†šå®¶å‰·ï¼&lt;img alt="" border="0" smilieid="5" src="https://www.discuss.com.hk/images/smilies/default2/huffy.gif"&gt;&lt;img alt="" border="0" smilieid="5" src="https://www.discuss.com.hk/images/smilies/default2/huffy.gif"/&gt;&lt;img alt="" border="0" smilieid="5" src="https://www.discuss.com.hk/images/smilies/default2/huffy.gif"/&gt;&lt;img alt="" border="0" smilieid="5" src="https://www.discuss.com.hk/images/smilies/default2/huffy.gif"/&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;br/&gt;Although opium was banned in Britain during the 19th century, the UK still insisted on exporting vast quantities of the drug to China via the East India Company. How awful was that?&lt;br/&gt;&lt;br/&gt;You've highlighted one of history's starkest moral hypocrisies. Britain's prohibition of opium domestically while aggressively exporting it to China was not just "awful"â€”it was a state-sanctioned crime against humanity with catastrophic consequences. Hereâ€™s why:&lt;br/&gt;&lt;br/&gt;### 1. **Blatant Hypocrisy &amp;amp; Racial Double Standard**&lt;br/&gt;- **UK Law**: Opium sales/use were strictly regulated in Britain (Pharmacy Act 1868), with medical professionals condemning its dangers.&lt;br/&gt;- **China Policy**: The UK knowingly flooded China with the same drug, dismissing Chinese sovereignty and public health. The East India Company (backed by the British Crown) monopolized opium production in Bengal and auctioned it to private traders for smuggling into China.&lt;br/&gt;&lt;br/&gt;### 2. **Scale of Destruction**&lt;br/&gt;- **Addiction Epidemic**: By 1838, ~12 million Chinese were addicted (4% of the population). Addiction ravaged communitiesâ€”laborers, soldiers, and elites alike.&lt;br/&gt;- **Economic Drain**: Silver flowed out of China to pay for opium, causing currency devaluation, inflation, and economic collapse.&lt;br/&gt;&lt;br/&gt;### 3. **Coercive Imperialism**&lt;br/&gt;- When China resisted (e.g., Lin Zexuâ€™s 1839 opium destruction), Britain launched the **Opium Wars** (1839â€“42, 1856â€“60).&lt;br/&gt;- **Outcome**: Unequal treaties (e.g., Treaty of Nanjing) forced China to cede Hong Kong, open ports to opium, and pay massive indemnitiesâ€”effectively legalizing the drug trade.&lt;br/&gt;&lt;br/&gt;### 4. **British Justification &amp;amp; Modern Reckoning**&lt;br/&gt;- **Propaganda**: Framed as "free trade" advocacy, ignoring that the "trade" was an addictive drug forced upon China.&lt;br/&gt;- **Critics at the Time**: Figures like William Gladstone condemned it as "infamous and atrocious." The *Times* later acknowledged (1897) it was a "national disgrace."&lt;br/&gt;- **Legacy**: This episode epitomizes colonial violenceâ€”prioritizing profit over human life, enabled by military supremacy.&lt;br/&gt;&lt;br/&gt;### Why This Matters Today&lt;br/&gt;The opium trade fueled Chinaâ€™s "Century of Humiliation," entrenched Western imperialism in Asia, and set precedents for modern drug cartel violence. Its brutality reminds us that historical "free trade" narratives often masked exploitation.&lt;br/&gt;&lt;br/&gt;The UKâ€™s actions werenâ€™t merely "awful"â€”they were a calculated, racially exploitative system that sacrificed millions for profit and power. Acknowledging this remains essential to understanding colonialismâ€™s true cost.&lt;/br&gt;&lt;/img&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br/&gt;&lt;br/&gt;&lt;br/&gt; &lt;!-- google_ad_section_end --&gt;&lt;/div&gt;</content><link href="https://www.discuss.com.hk/viewthread.php?tid=32002818&amp;extra=page%3D1%26amp%3Bfilter%3D0%26amp%3Borderby%3Ddateline%26amp%3Bascdesc%3DDESC&amp;tr_h=1298815158689744ce4f0cf4_97207678"/><published>2025-08-09T12:19:54+08:00</published></entry><entry><id>cfcf14e4bd5a8f9cf8c52358a27f97ca</id><title>é»è§£åŸºå­”ç™»é©ç†±è¦é©—æ ¸é…¸å˜…</title><upda